"We could, for instance, begin with cleaning up our 
 language by no longer calling a bug a bug but by 
 calling it an error. It is much more honest because 
 it squarely puts the blame where it belongs, viz. 
 with the programmer who made the error. The animistic 
 metaphor of the bug that maliciously sneaked in while 
 the programmer was not looking is intellectually dishonest 
 as it disguises that the error is the programmer's own creation. 
 The nice thing of this simple change of vocabulary is that it has 
 such a profound effect: while, before, a program with only one bug 
 used to be "almost correct", afterwards a program with an error is 
 just "wrong" (because in error)."
  -- E. W. Dijkstra, 
    http://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/EWD/transcriptions/EWD10xx/EWD1036.html
